Results of the antibacterial and antifungal activities were presented in Table 1
                        . Antibacterial and antifungal activities of TCDs increased linearly with increase in concentration of TCDs (mg/mL) which reveals that TCDs can effectively inhibit the growth of the bacteria in a concentration dependent manner. As compared with standard drugs, the results revealed that TCDs inhibit the growth of E. coli and C. albicans more effectively compared to other tested microbes (S. aureus, K. pneumoniea and P. aeruginosa). The inhibition zone measured ranging from 7 to 12mm for all the bacterial organisms and 14mm for fungal strain (Fig. 2
                        ). The mechanism behind the lysis of bacterial cell wall by the synthetic compounds and QDs have been previously reported, that might be due to loss of electrolyte causing death of the organism [25,26,28]. In this present study, morphological changes in C. albicans were monitored using confocal microscopy which clearly indicated the interacting efficiency of TCDs with fungal cells (Fig. 3
                        ). Fluorescent ability of TCDs was assessed directly under confocal microscopy without any fluorescent tagging. Fungal cells which bound to the TCDs only exhibited fluorescence, whereas cells without TCDs do not exhibit the fluorescence property. The adherence of the synthesized compound to the fungi can be based on many factors like size of the cell, water resistance, charge and ligand arrangement of the cells [29]. The cell wall of C. albicans is made up of carbohydrates (80–90%), protein (6–25%) and lipids (1–7%). They maintain the rigidity of the cell, provide structure to the cell and protect the protoplast. Reports are available which show that the QDs get bound to the surface of the microorganism and thereby inducing ROS by transferring oxygen molecules which create the singlet molecular oxygen (1O2) and hydroxyl free radicals (OH) formation, affecting the oxidative and antioxidant balance which in turn destroy the biomolecules found in the cell wall leading to the lysis of the cell [29,30].
